To proxy requests in an ASP.NET Core API, you can use the `HttpClient` class to send the request to the target endpoint and then return the response to the client. Here's an example of how you can do this:

```csharp
[ApiController]
[Route("api/[controller]")]
public class MyController : ControllerBase
{
    private readonly HttpClient _httpClient;

    public MyController(IHttpClientFactory httpClientFactory)
    {
        _httpClient = httpClientFactory.CreateClient();
    }

    [HttpGet]
    public async Task<IActionResult> Get()
    {
        var response = await _httpClient.GetAsync("https://target-endpoint.com/api/data");

        if (response.IsSuccessStatusCode)
        {
            return Ok(await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync());
        }
        else
        {
            return StatusCode((int)response.StatusCode, await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync());
        }
    }
}
```

However, this approach has some limitations. For example, it doesn't handle CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) properly, and it doesn't allow you to easily configure the proxy behavior.

A better approach is to use the `HttpClientFactory` to create an instance of `HttpClient` that is configured to handle proxy requests. You can then use this instance to send requests to the target endpoint.

